if;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAAAAACH5BAEKAAEALAAAAAABAAEAAAICTAEAOw==\" media=\"(min-width: 500px)\" data-srcset=\"https://images.food52.com/tlSzww_J65bEUBg1pBnPHr9exlo=/768x1034/afc2871c-6f06-4735-9761-20ba057eea85--Screenshot_2025-01-31_at_1.48.17_PM.png, https://images.food52.com/5e9FXDUxvinoXLDuf7CY-eDYnXE=/1536x2068/afc2871c-6f06-4735-9761-20ba057eea85--Screenshot_2025-01-31_at_1.48.17_PM.png 2x\"/\u003e\u003csource srcset=\"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAAAAACH5BAEKAAEALAAAAAABAAEAAAICTAEAOw==\" type=\"image/webp\" data-srcset=\"https://images.food52.com/9jlW1bffJ7DXFqvKVshbN0HP2gk=/375x505/filters:format(webp)/afc2871c-6f06-4735-9761-20ba057eea85--Screenshot_2025-01-31_at_1.48.17_PM.png, https://images.food52.com/1A5nZXHKW62P-_JuM3iFdDIcq60=/750x1010/filters:format(webp)/afc2871c-6f06-4735-9761-20ba057eea85--Screenshot_2025-01-31_at_1.48.17_PM.png 2x\"/\u003e\u003cimg srcset=\"https://images.food52.com/HGDmx1sgpNT7agEoKOG-1KqKJeE=/375x505/afc2871c-6f06-4735-9761-20ba057eea85--Screenshot_2025-01-31_at_1.48.17_PM.png, https://images.food52.com/VXcms7HhWXV4ali0Nz45rfD3L9M=/750x1010/afc2871c-6f06-4735-9761-20ba057eea85--Screenshot_2025-01-31_at_1.48.17_PM.png 2x\" alt=\"\" width=\"964\" height=\"1298\" data-expand=\"750\" data-srcset=\"https://images.food52.com/HGDmx1sgpNT7agEoKOG-1KqKJeE=/375x505/afc2871c-6f06-4735-9761-20ba057eea85--Screenshot_2025-01-31_at_1.48.17_PM.png, https://images.food52.com/VXcms7HhWXV4ali0Nz45rfD3L9M=/750x1010/afc2871c-6f06-4735-9761-20ba057eea85--Screenshot_2025-01-31_at_1.48.17_PM.png 2x\"/\u003e\u003c/picture\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\n    \u003c/div\u003e\n\n      \u003cfigcaption\u003e\n\n          \u003cspan\u003ePhoto by Noah Tanen\u003c/span\u003e\n      \u003c/figcaption\u003e\n  \u003c/figure\u003e\n\n              \u003cp\u003eSo what actually makes them better in New York? In my opinion, it’s the people. Bagels arrived in New York City by way of Ashkenazi Jewish immigrants from Poland in the late 1800s, and ever since, New Yorkers have been perfecting the craft of \u003ca href=\"https://www.tiktok.com/@utopiabagels/video/7462380740953623854\" target=\"_blank\"\u003ebagel rolling\u003c/a\u003e and \u003ca href=\"https://www.npr.org/sections/thesalt/2015/05/21/405190434/chew-on-this-the-science-of-great-nyc-bagels-its-not-the-water\" target=\"_blank\"\u003eboiling\u003c/a\u003e, holding on fiercely to tried and true techniques and recipes even in the modern era.\u003c/p\u003e\n              \u003cp\u003eAfter all, this kind of passionate local culture is what makes regional food special. When you have a history spanning centuries and generations of people making the same food, often in competition with one another, it’s that pride and local association which produces greatness. It’s why Philadelphia makes the best cheesesteaks, Texas has the best barbecue, and why New York City makes the greatest bagels.\u003c/p\u003e\n              \u003cp\u003eEven if you’re not in or from New York City, you can make \u003ca href=\"https://food52.com/recipes/22934-homemade-bagels?srsltid=AfmBOooiC7eLLsnXLYZIKSIm27a43ZUTwFm1W4ejCB2a5aXK2P6coglR\"\u003ehomemade bagels\u003c/a\u003e yourself. I’ll be trying my hand as well. Stay tuned to \u003ca href=\"https://www.instagram.com/food52/?hl=en\" target=\"_blank\"\u003eour Instagram\u003c/a\u003e for an upcoming episode of Noah Tackles: Bagels coming next week.\u003c/p\u003e\n              \n  \n\n\n\n              \u003chr/\u003e\n\n              \n              \u003ccenter\u003e\n\u003cem\u003eHave you ever made bagels from scratch? Let us know in the comments!\u003c/em\u003e\n\u003c/center\u003e\n          \u003c/div\u003e\n\n            \n\n\n            \n            \n\n\n\n            \n\u003cdiv\u003e\n  \n\n    \u003cp\u003e\n      Test Kitchen Content Creator at Food52\n    \u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/div\u003e\n\n        \u003c/div\u003e\n\n  \n  \u003cdiv\u003e\n      \u003ch3\u003ePopular on Food52\u003c/h3\u003e\n      \n    \u003c/div\u003e\n\n  \n\u003c/div\u003e\u003c/div\u003e",
